So I repaired it with a switch that I had in my shed. You can see this in the photographs. It has worked successfully since then and so I foresee no future issues.

If that puts you off, then I am sorry. The item still has a good paint job and no rust in the body of the machine. You can see it running. Actually I made a video which I will try to upload for you to see. The G.W. Gail & Ax Company was founded by Mr. George W. Gail in 1850. By 1855 Mr. Ax had joined the firm as the company was just starting their growth spurt, and already had made an addition to their original building. With the addition the building was quickly five stories tall . In the companies heyday the firm employed about 350 skilled tobacco men.

The G. W. Gail & Ax Company produced smoking tobacco, cut plug, chewing tobacco and snuff. Along with the famous Navy brand, their second largest seller was call “Little Joker”. Most of their tobacco product was grown in Virginia, North Carolina, Kentucky and Maryland. The production of tobacco eventually reached over three million pounds of finished product and the Gail & Ax firm helped propel Baltimore to become one of the leading tobacco production cities in the United States. The G. W. Gail & Ax Tobacco Works was famous for their leading brand, Navy Cut Plug Chewing Tobacco.

At the age of eleven Frank Bruno was sent to reform school. At thirty-three he was crowned undisputed heavyweight champion of the world. At forty-one he was committed to Goodmayes Psychiatric Hospital. Now, for the first time, Frank Bruno tells his real story- how the tearaway kid became one of Britain's best-loved sports stars; how he was written off, but came back to win the world championship - at the fourth attempt; his descent into mental illness; and his painful journey back to health. This is a story that Frank has to tell - it is part biography, part therapy. He wants to show how mental illness can swat down the strongest man or woman. He wants people to know what he went through, and how, with the help of his family, he's now recovering. Frank Bruno is a man who has been right to the top and right to the very bottom. He is a great athlete and a national treasure. Everyone knows him. At least, everyone thinks they do. Because the story he reveals here will make you change your mind. Painfully honest, moving, at times shocking, this is the book no one should be without. Very good condition.

After months of cold, wet, doom and gloom, Summer had finally arrived. On one particularly hot afternoon, Barbara Queue, a highly respected local lady, decided to host a barbeque for her friends, family and neighbours. The afternoon seemed to be going very well with everyone eating, drinking and getting along. As the dark shroud of the evening drew in though, tragedy struck and a body was found at Barbara's house. While the police were going about their business, the guests all set about trying to solve the murder to exonerate their names, but what other sinister motives were going on underneath the surface? What secrets were people hiding, who would resort to murder to keep those secrets hidden and who was the unfortunate sole who had burnt their last sausage? Just like the traditional English Summer time, things are about to get very stormy! Can you work out who was responsible for the Summer Slaying or will you be the one who is Bumped off at the Barbeque! The suspects are:

About Ultimate Murder Mystery Games

We have been supplying unique and entertaining murder mystery games to the world since 2008. Since then we have sold our games in over 40 countries around the world to thousands of satisfied customers. From there, it is up to each player where they take their character and how they choose to play them. Fun costume suggestions, entertaining "secret tasks" and full confessions from the guilty party all contribute to a truly enjoyable Murder Mystery Party!

I'm now 60, but when I was 16, I made this leather jacket from bits my mother had left over from her work as a seamstress. She made leather clothes, slippers and a whole host of other stuff.

Anyway, in amongst all the sheepskin, leather off cuts, ends of cotton and boxes of material, I drew out the pattern on paper, cut the leather, stitched it, cut the tassels and put in the zip, all under the watchful eye of mother who was frightened to death I was going to run a three cornered needle over my fingers, and stitch myself to the leather, or the bed of her machine.

These photos are the result of what it looks like now after 35 years of being in a suitcase. I wore it everywhere until I put on too much weight and had to put it in storage.

This is my son modelling it for me (now 20). He says all the clothes he buys are medium, and it seems to fit him ok. The sleeves are long because in those days I had long arms, just like my son, so there was no skimping on the length.

It is unique because there is not another one like it anywhere in the world. If you like a bit of oneness, then I hope you will enjoy wearing it as much as I did.

Shakey: Neil Young's biography by Jimmy McDonough (Paperback)

Neil Young is one of rock and roll's most important, influential and enigmatic figures, an intensely reticent artist who has granted no writer access to his inner sanctum - until now. Shakey is the whole story of Young's incredible life and career: from his childhood in Canada to the founding of folk-rock pioneers Buffalo Springfield; the bleary conglomeration of Crazy Horse and the monstrous success of Crosby, Stills, Nash and Young; to the depths of the Tonight's the Night depravity and the Geffen years; and Young's unprecedented nineties 'comeback'.

Shakey (the title refers to one of Young's many aliases) is also the compelling human story of a lonely kid for whom music was the only outlet, a driven yet tortured figure who controlled his epilepsy via 'mind over matter', an oddly passionate model train mogul who, inspired by his own son's struggle with cerebral palsy, became a major activist in the quest to help those with the condition.

This long-awaited, unprecedented story of a rock 'n' roll legend is uniquely told through the interwoven voices of McDonough - biographer, critic, historian, obsessive fan - and the ever-cantankerous (but slyly funny) Young himself.

This is the lesser-spotted Leica M Summicron 50mm F/2 lens, with near-focusing range.

The mighty Ken Rockwell refers to this beauty as “LEICA's greatest 50mmlens ever,” and “the most important, useful and critical lens in any 35mm or full-frame system,” on the basis “every lens before had slightly weaker opticsand much weaker mechanics, while later lenses have much weaker mechanical construction,” and “no LEICA lens has ever focused as close or as precisely.”

This particular iteration of the Leica M Summicron 50mm F/2 lens is hard to come by. It offers the same premium output of the standard Summicron 50mm, which means beautiful and extremely crisp shots even fully open which just get sharper and sharper the more you stop down, stunning colours, tones and shades always and world-leading bokeh every time, but also near-shooting like no other Leica lens ever created, opening up a whole host of possibilities for Leica use that simply aren't accessible with alternative M-mount lenses and equivalents.

It comes fully equipped with an original Leica UV Haze filter, perfect for black & white photography, original front and back caps and lens hood, and Leica goggles, which are in mint condition. The goggles also have a nifty small carrying case which looks basically unused.

Small and relatively lightweight yet still built like a tank (it’s a Leica after all!), the lens is in absolutely mint condition, with no scratches, dents or marks on the body, and the glass itself is pristine, dazzlingly clear with no scratches, haze, dust or fungus in sight. Focus and aperture ring movement is also extremely tactile, smooth, crisp and fast. Any questions please ask

Hand raked alpaca manure in large (typically 10-12kg) strong sealed bags, ideal for your garden allotment or seeding.

Special offer, buy 4 get one free!

Why Alpaca manure?

Alpaca manure is the best natural fertilizer for vegetable, flower gardens and even house plants. It's lower in organic matter than manure from other farm animals, but still has enough to improve soil texture and water-holding capacity. Alpaca manure (or beans) do not have to be aged or cured; They will not burn; the plants it comes in contact with and can be applied rather carelessly without fussing.

The alpaca's 3-stomach digestive system processes food so efficiently seeds do not survive to become weeds in your garden, as with cow or horse manure. They are nature’s composters. It also has comparatively high levels of nitrogen and potassium which are major plant nutrients and part of the well-known N-P-K indicator on fertilizer bags, and an indication of good fertilizer value.

Alpaca manure has a very low odour (practically none) which makes it a fantastic fertilizer to work with. Good soil health will reduce disease and pest problems and keep your plants happy and healthy throughout the year.

Although alpaca manure starts out in a pellet or bean form, it breaks down quickly and can be used without extensive “ageing”

Use Alpaca beans safely on your houseplants, just spoon a little into the soil, and the fertilizer will gradually release as you water. It is odourless and harmless to pets.

Sprinkle some Alpaca beans around your plants or trees, mix with a little dirt and every time you water your plants you are fertilizing them at the same time.

For seedlings, use alpaca tea. Mix 1 part alpaca pellets with 2 parts water and let it sit from 5-12 hours. Within 24 hours of the first application, you will begin to see the difference in your seedling.

Alpaca beans are great for delicate plants and terrific for soil health. Adding it to your garden or lawn.

Please note that contents may include foliage, straw, soil and in some cases acorns and other seedlings. weight varies according to water content.

I am selling this fantastic W Temlett Banjo. The instrument probably dates from 1869 onwards until 1900.

It is 5 string closed back and is understood to be a fore runner design for the zither banjo. The instrument has mother of pearl in lays. The neck looks straight. However, I am not expert by any means.

There is a small hole to the neck (see photograph) and some of the hoop screws are missing along with a poor substitute screw.

The instrument was stringed circa 8 years ago. However it has never been played. There are some surface indentations which is to be expected for the age of the instrument. Apart from these, the finish is good.

Go to Soundcloud for a short clip of the instrument being played. It has a gorgeous warm sound https://soundcloud.com/doctordidge-1/w-temlett-banjo

There is no case.

The starting price is low for the quality of instrument on offer and gives someone the chance to own a quality vintage banjo.

I have owned this Technics Digital Audio Tape Deck from new. I bought it to complement a small home recording studio, but only ever used it to master a few tracks. Apart from that it is practically unused, and has been lying in the attic since the 1990s.


It is in excellent condition, with no marks at all on the front panel, and only a minor scratch on the surface (from the feet of the CD player that once sat on top). All marks are shown in the pictures.


The specs of this machine are impressive. It was the consumer version of Panasonic’s SV-3200 professional deck, known for its reliability and quality. It can search a tape at up to 400 times normal playback speed, and rewind a 2 hour DAT tape in 27 seconds. The sampling is 16 bit linear, and able to record and play back at 32, 44.1 and 48 kHz (selected automatically from the input signal). It has analogue (RCA) inputs and outputs, and both coaxial and optical digital inputs and outputs. It has a headphone socket with its own volume control. Other specs:


Frequency response; 2 Hz – 22,000 Hz (+/- 0.5 dB)

Dynamic range: >90 dB

Signal to noise ratio: > 90 dB

The Beatles 1962-66 double album on red vinyl.

The Beatles 1967-70 double album on blue vinyl.

These are the originals released around 1976. They are brand new, bought by me as a young lad. I can't exactly remember how many sides have been played, but I seem to recall it was only one side out of the possible eight sides of the entire set.

So I am selling these as brand new, never played.

For heaven's sake, I don't even know why I bought them, I don't even like the Beatles! Never did. I just think I liked the idea they were coloured vinyl, which was unusual, and therefore collectable, when all the rest of my records were black vinyl.

I kept my Batmobile with the flames coming out the back, my old Johnny 7 gun, a stack of Superman comics that was taller than me and lots of other things that nowadays are worth a small fortune. I just knew how to look after stuff, and have sold a lot of it over the years.

Anyway, I came across these as we moved house again, and I figured it was time I went through the things I've never even looked at for decades, like my record collection.

These Beatles records have been in a secure record case for all that time, never having seen the light of day since the day they went in there. They are therefore crisp and bright colours, not having been bleached by the sun or exposure to the atmosphere.

The outer and inner sleeves are perfect, with no creases or blemishes. And the records themselves are flawless.

I know I'm asking a lot for them. There is a blue album on Gumtree I saw this week selling for £100. And recent sales on record valuation sites have shown that both red and blue, sold as a set, twice reached just under £120 within the last couple of years.

I'm quite sure that any collector would appreciate the sheer pristine nature of these two albums and would then also agree that they may be worth a little premium. I think I'd also rather not split them up, but of course, everything is open to negotiation.
